  <h2>How to (Respectfully) Spot a Tree Trout</h2>
  <p><em>Oncorhynchus arboris</em></p>
  
  <p>The Rocky Mountain tree trout is best observed indirectly.</p>
  
  <p>Despite decades of reported sightings, confirmed visual documentation remains elusive - owing not to rarity alone, but to the species' exceptional camouflage, arboreal habits, and apparent preference for remaining unobserved.</p>

  <h2>Identifying Signs of Presence</h2>
  <p>Rather than scanning branches for fish-shaped silhouettes, experienced observers recommend attending to secondary indicators, including:</p>
  <ul>
    <li>Subtle branch jostling without wind</li>
    <li>Isolated droplets falling from canopy pools on otherwise dry mornings</li>
    <li>Momentary flashes of mottled orange or olive, quickly reabsorbed into bark texture</li>
    <li>Invertebrate silence, particularly among aphids and beetles, suggesting recent predation</li>
  </ul>
  
  <p>Many hikers report the unmistakable sound of "something wet reconsidering its choices" above them. While not diagnostic, this auditory cue appears frequently in credible accounts.</p>

  <h2>Preferred Habitat</h2>
  <p>Tree trout favor high-elevation coniferous forests where:</p>
  <ul>
    <li>Streams intersect mature pine and fir stands</li>
    <li>Epiphytic mats retain moisture</li>
    <li>Fog drip sustains small canopy reservoirs</li>
  </ul>
  
  <p>They are most active in early morning and late evening, particularly during seasonal transitions when movement between aquatic and arboreal environments increases.</p>

  <h2>Ethical Observation Guidelines</h2>
  <p>Tree trout are sensitive to disturbance. To minimize impact:</p>
  <ul>
    <li>Do not shake branches "just to see"</li>
    <li>Avoid climbing trees near streams</li>
    <li>Refrain from tossing snacks upward, no matter how fish-like</li>
    <li>Observe quietly and let uncertainty do the rest</li>
  </ul>
  
  <p>Remember: the absence of confirmation is not failure - it is participation.</p>

